<DOC><DOCNO>  ZF109-732-533  </DOCNO><DOCID>09 732 533.andO;</DOCID><JOURNAL>Telecommunications  Dec 1990 v24 n12 p41(1).andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>Why is fiber deployment taking so long?andO;</TITLE><AUTHOR>Cadogan, William J.andM;</AUTHOR><TEXT><ABSTRACT>Fiberization is going on in the US, but it is taking longer thananticipated.andP;  One reason is that the perceived value of theapplications, such as videoconferencing, has not been great enoughto produce enough profit.andP;  In addition, the growth of fiber willdepend, in part, on how rapidly a new national policy is embraced,one that will promote a competitive market.andP;  Much will also dependupon how quickly the industry develops applications.andP;  Anotherobstacle is the fact that copper is durable and already in place,so that fiber is primarily being installed in new service areas.andO;To assure a place in the global market, there should be acommitment to creating applications for the technology, such ashigh-definition television.andM;</ABSTRACT></TEXT><DESCRIPT>Topic:     ApplicationsMarketingHigh-Definition TelevisionVideoconferencingTechnologyProfitGovernment RegulationFiber opticsCritique.andM;</DESCRIPT></DOC>